This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama commemorating the 150th anniversary of the 13th Amendment to the United States Constitution. The 13th Amendment, ratified on December 6, 1865, abolished slavery in the United States and marked the end of a painful chapter in American history. The proclamation honors the millions of slaves who suffered and rededicates the nation to the principles of liberty and equality. It highlights the courage of individuals, including President Lincoln, abolitionists, and volunteers of the Underground Railroad, who fought for the rights of slaves. The proclamation also acknowledges the ongoing fight against modern-day slavery and human trafficking. The article calls on the people of the United States to observe the anniversary with appropriate programs and activities.